  <hr />

  <h2 id="ez-clone-setup">EZ Clone Setup</h2>
  <p>I run the EZ Clone 16 site system. It's a recirculating aeroponic cloner — the pump mists the stem ends continuously, which triggers rapid root development without a medium. No rockwool, no soil, no cubes. Just stem in air with constant moisture.</p>

  <h3>Water</h3>
  <p>RO water pH'd to 5.8. Start clean — no nutrients, no additives beyond the rooting solution. Clones don't need to eat yet, they need to root.</p>

  <h3>Rooting Solution</h3>
  <p>10 drops of GH Rapid Start per gallon. That's it. Rapid Start contains IBA (indole-3-butyric acid) which triggers root initiation. Don't over-complicate the reservoir — clean water and rooting hormone is the whole recipe.</p>

  <h3>Light</h3>
  <p>150 PAR. Low and even. Clones don't need intensity — they need stability. High light stresses cuttings before they have roots to support transpiration. Keep it gentle until roots appear.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="the-process">The Process</h2>

  <h3>Taking The Cut</h3>
  <p>Cut at a 45° angle below a node. 4-6 inches is the right length. Remove lower leaves, leave 2-3 sets at the top. The cut end goes directly into the cloner neoprene collar — no rooting gel needed in an aeroponic system, the misting handles it.</p>

  <h3>Timeline</h3>
  <p>1-2 weeks in the EZ Clone before roots are ready to transplant. Hawaii's warmth actually helps here — root development is faster in warm ambient temps. I typically see root tips at day 7-10, transplant-ready roots by day 10-14.</p>

  <h3>What To Watch For</h3>
  <p>Healthy clones wilt slightly for the first 24-48 hours then perk back up as root initiation begins. If a clone is still wilted at day 5, check the collar seal — it may not be getting adequate misting. Yellowing lower leaves is normal. New growth at the top means roots are developing.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="into-coco">Into Coco</h2>
  <p>Once roots are 1-2 inches long the clone is ready to transplant. Two options depending on the destination:</p>

  <h3>Option 1 — Straight Into Buffered Coco</h3>
  <p>For plants going into AutoPots or staying in an indoor coco system. Transplant into buffered coco in a 1 or 2 gallon pot. Start feeding at 1.0-1.2 EC (500-600 PPM on the 500 scale) from day one. The root system is small so keep EC conservative for the first week.</p>

  <h3>Option 2 — 50/50 Light Mix and Coco</h3>
  <p>For plants eventually going outdoors. The 50/50 blend of light potting mix and coco gives a slightly more forgiving transition medium — a little more buffering capacity than pure coco, which helps when moving plants that will eventually hit outdoor soil biology. Still feed at 1.0-1.2 EC, same as pure coco.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="outdoor-transition">Outdoor Transition</h2>
  <p>The goal of the indoor coco stage for outdoor plants is building a solid root ball before hitting the ground. 1, 2, or 3 gallon pots depending on how much veg time you want indoors before the move.</p>
  <p>A plant with a developed root ball transplants into outdoor soil with far less stress than a freshly rooted clone. The established root system can immediately start exploring the new medium instead of spending energy just surviving the transition.</p>
  <p>Harden off before the final move — move plants to a shaded outdoor spot for 3-5 days before full sun exposure. Hawaii's UV is intense and plants coming from indoor lighting need time to adjust. Skipping hardening off causes light bleaching and stress that sets the plant back 2 weeks.</p>

  <div class="hawaii-notes">
    <p>Hawaii's ambient temperature runs warm year round which speeds up cloning significantly. My EZ Clone sits in a space that stays 75-82°F without any heating mat — root development is consistently faster here than what I see documented from colder climates.</p>
    <p>The outdoor transition is where Hawaii's UV becomes a real factor. I've burned plants moving them from a 150 PAR indoor light directly to full Oahu sun. Now I always go: EZ Clone → indoor coco veg → 3-5 days partial shade outdoor → full sun. That hardening window makes a visible difference in how cleanly plants adapt.</p>
    <p>On the 50/50 light mix and coco blend for outdoor-bound plants — I use a local potting mix from Koolau Farmers. Nothing fancy. The coco provides structure and drainage, the potting mix provides some biology and buffering. Works well as a bridge medium before the plant hits the outdoor soil ecosystem.</p>
  </div>

